{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616525"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:04:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:04:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16403"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16403"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.07,0.61,0.04,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9094"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74858"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9094"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16403"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60364"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1531"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10378"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21599"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21602"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74858"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with gradually worsening memory over the past year. Although she has difficulty recalling her recent medical appointments and family visits, she maintains detailed knowledge about historical events and can engage in discussions about current political developments.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following memory systems is most likely to remain intact in this clinical scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Episodic memory","Procedural memory","Semantic memory","Sensory memory","Working memory"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESemantic memory\u003C/strong\u003E represents our stored knowledge of facts, meanings, and understanding of the world around us. This memory system often remains functional in early cognitive decline, allowing individuals to maintain their accumulated knowledge and understanding of general information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlternative memory systems and why they are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpisodic memory\u003C/strong\u003E involves remembering personal experiences and autobiographical events. This system commonly shows early deterioration in cognitive decline, as evidenced by difficulty remembering recent appointments and conversations.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcedural memory\u003C/strong\u003E encompasses learned skills and automatic behaviours. While often preserved in cognitive decline, this system relates to motor skills rather than factual knowledge.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESensory memory\u003C/strong\u003E briefly retains incoming sensory information for processing. This basic memory system does not relate to long-term storage of knowledge.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWorking memory\u003C/strong\u003E provides temporary storage for ongoing cognitive tasks. This short-term system differs from the long-term storage of general knowledge.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pattern of preserved general knowledge despite impaired memory for recent events is frequently observed in age-related cognitive decline and early dementia syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Semantic memory refers to general knowledge, facts, and concepts about the world not tied to personal experiences.","Different types of memory systems serve distinct cognitive functions and are processed in different brain regions.","Semantic memory typically remains preserved in early stages of cognitive decline while episodic memory is often affected first."],"references":["Raslau FD, Klein AP, Ulmer JL, Mathews V, Mark LP. Memory part 1: overview. AJNR Am J Neuroradiol. 2014 Nov-Dec;35(11):2058-60. doi: 10.3174/ajnr.A4059. Epub 2014 Jul 17. PMID: 25034776; PMCID: PMC7965175.","Mariani C, Sacco L, Spinnler H, Venneri A. General Knowledge of the World: a standardised assessment. Neurol Sci. 2002 Oct;23(4):161-75. doi: 10.1007/s100720200057. PMID: 12536285.","Jawabri KH, Cascella M. Physiology, Explicit Memory. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554551/","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60364"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16403"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60364"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T23:16:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T23:17:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9094"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74858"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"